<br>
This is the first story that I have ever written, and it is full of holes, but you can only patch something up so much before it gets all fucked up.  Feel free to criticize it.  Peace.  <br>
<br>
Pullem (Retired monk of Promethian Order)<br>
<br>
<br>
The Search For Tranquility<br>
<br>
<br>
Chapter 1<br>
<br>
The cobblestones of the street vanished and I fell through the world.  My body started to flain and twist as I dropped into the blackness surrounding.  Looking up, I saw the world from below as a rectangular plane that shrank in size until it was a mere twinkle on the black horizon; and then it also faded.  My senses had nothing to perceive; I had been swept to a place of nonexistance.  I could not hear my voice when I screamed, nor could I register the passing of time.  In this void, light had no definition, and I had to use my fingers to check if my eyes were open or closed.  My mind became restless, and I found myself in uneasy thought; as I traveled backwards in time and then forward again.  <br>
<br>
The journey back was not long, because in the life that I had known, I had lived for only one year.  I was a grown man that awoke in a child's bed, but unlike children, whose nightmares fade when they wake, I awoke to a nightmare.  When I gained consciousness, my body felt as if it had been torn apart; I hurt everywhere.  Each breath that I took was strenuous; my hands felt like they had been severed, and when I tried to move my leg, it felt as if someone, other than me, was twisting it in the wrong direction.  I figured that I was either in hell or living, or a combination of the words.  After a few minutes, I fell back asleep.<br>
<br>
I drifted in and out of consciousness for days, but eventually, the pain lessened and I awoke.  When my eyes adjusted, I glanced around and found that I was in a miniature room.  The bed that I had been lying on was three feet too small.  The furniture, which consisted of a bedside table and desk, could have been used by children.  It was as if the world had shrunk, or I had grown.  In addition to the smallness of the room's items, it appeared that I was underground; the room's walls were made of dirt, and overhead, I saw roots that hung down like tiny fingers poking through the ceiling.  Beyond the door, I heard the playful bark of a dog and children in song.<br>
<br>
It took me a few minutes for my senses to adjust, and when I was about to sleep again, the round door banged open.  A halfling entered.  He was short, but in the small room, he appeared to fit, and I was out of place.  He smiled at me and said, &quot;The monk had been--<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>resurrected</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Am I dead?&quot;  I asked.  I thought that maybe I had passed on, and that by a cruel joke, Bristlebane had bartered for my sould, thus forcing me to live in a halfling heaven that was really a human hell.<br>
<br>
&quot;No.  No.  Not dead, but almost; you are in Rivervale,&quot; the halfling said.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Who are you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am Lum Linder Claw.  And you can thank me later when you get your strength back.  I dragged you out of the river near Runnyeye.  The goblins in there almost killed you, but I fixed you up, and luckily, no actually, thanks to Bristlebane I was able to revive you.  I need to you bandages, so just sit tight, and try not to holler.&quot;  I looked down at my body.  Almost the entirety of my torso had been swathed in bandages, some of which were stained pink.  &quot;This might hurt a bit.  So let's just talk while I do this.&quot;  He started to unwrap the bandages.<br>
<br>
&quot;So goblins got me?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I dragged you out of the river.  What do you remember?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I remember nothing, other than waking up here.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What is your name?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Turan.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Turan, you got cracked on the head pretty good, and it is going to take some time remember. . . if you ever do.  At least you still know who you are.  I have saved a few of you heros from Runnyeye, and some were worse than you.  They didn't remember anything--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But I don't remember anything--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You remembered your name.&quot;  Lum was right.  I remembered my name, and more.  I was Turan, a human monk of the Ashen Order.  I was 28 years old.  I had jet black hair.  My frame was small.  I remembered these facts, but recalling any event in the past was like trying to decipher a book written in a foreign language.  I knew that the book told a story, but I did not know what it said.<br>
<br>
Our talk continued as Lum re-dressed the bandages.  Occasionally I had to bit down on my lip so I would not scream out in pain.  During the process, I looked down at the wounds and I was aghast.  It was as if my body had been the canvas for a psychotic painter, but instead of using a brush, the person had used a knife.  My body had been painted red.  Each line was a slash.  Each scribble was a piercing.  And well. . . the bump on my head was teh artist's signature.  When Lum finished, he got up and said, &quot;In time--hopefully--you will remember some of you past, but I have another question for you, &quot;Who are Mongar and Taffy?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't know?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Never mind then.  Maybe you will find out later.  The reason I ask is because you kept repeating their names over and over when you were unconscious.  For three months, you did.  But anyway, I am going to leave you now, you need some rest.  Later I will bring you some fresh jum-jum.&quot;<br>
<br>
In the next months, Lum and I became friends.  I have never experienced this type of generous altruism--not that I could have remembered--but I knew that Lum was special.  Occasionally, I would ask him. &quot;Lum why are you helping me?&quot;<br>
<br>
He would smile and say, &quot;I am not helping you.  I am merely practing my spells.&quot;<br>
<br>
It took my body three months to recover, and during this time I would often question Lum about my memory.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lum, Lum,&quot; I would say.  &quot;When are you going to help me remember?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I can't help you with that, but in time, your memories. . . hopefully, will return.&quot;  Some of my memories did return, but they were facts about general information, not events.  This lack of information was frusterating, and on occasion my temper would ignite.  It was as if my history was wrapped up in two names that gave me purpose, but not direction.  I needed to find Mongar and Taffy, but I did not know where to begin.  I lived with this question for four months, and as I recovered, my restlessness increased.<br>
<br>
I would often have nightmares.  Sometimes I thought these images were of the past.  Others I believed portended my future.  It was impossible to tell because when you have no memory, time becomes confusing, and you beging to see things, not as how they are, but as how you want them to be.  Eventually--perhaps by chance--Lum gave me another clue.  <br>
<br>
Since I had arrived, I heard the constant warning from Lum about the dangers of Runnyeye, but it occurred to me that the dangers to a small halfling might not be equivelent to that of a human monk.  I questioned him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lum, why is Runnyeye so dangerous?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Goblins, hoards of them, evil, vile, lathe, and deadly. . . very deadly--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But, what do you think I was doing there?  What would a human monk be doing in Runnyeye?&quot;  He paused.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, I will tell; I think you were trying to pass through the caves.  It is the fastest way to the Karanas.  You cut through Runnyeye, then go through the Gorge of King Xorbe, and then you are in the Plains of Karana. . . And I found a not in your pocket.  Let me get it for you.&quot;  He returned with a small tattered piece of parchment.  On it, I saw two names: &quot;Southern Karnana, and Brother Qwinn.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Chapter 2<br>
<br>
Blackness upon blackness as I continued through the void.  My thoughts advanced, and I saw myself standing in front of a small cave that bore into the mountain.  I was staring into the mouth of Runnyeye.  I was there against Lum's advice--he had wanted me to go to the Freeport dojo to learn of my origins--but I had chosen to cross through Misty Thicket to travel to Southern Karana.  Two goblins stood in front of Runnyeye.  Each was short about a halfling's height, but unlike the halflings whose cute rounded bellies, hairy feet, and small stature had charmed me, the goblins were repulsive.  It was as if they were created by a lazy God, and what I saw was merely the blueprint of something with greated intention.  They looked viscous but for unknown reasons--I was not afraid.  <br>
<br>
I approached the cave staring at the goblins' wide yellow eyes, thin frames, and crooked postures.  The goblins backed away.  I pointed to the cave.  &quot;I need to get through to the gorge.&quot;  I said.  They did not respond, but continued retreating.  Then one said, in broken common, <br>
<br>
&quot;Mooto, will be back soon--go around the other way.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Let him come,&quot;  I said.  The goblins looked to each other with fearful expressions.  It was as if they were measuring their chances of survival by judging the likelihood that the other would flee.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, Ok, we let you pass, but can you spare some--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I have no money.&quot;  It was true.  I have never carried anything of value other than a backpack filled with rations, bandages, and pumice stones.  &quot;Stand aside, and let me pass.&quot;  They did not repsond.  My temper flared and I struck out at one of the goblins.<br>
<br>
My fist crashed down on one of the goblins' head like a hammer.  It shattered the goblin's skull and he toppled to the ground.  The other goblin did not have time to flee.  He became my next victim as I struck him in the stomach with a kick.  He fell to the ground, clutching at his gut.  I approached.<br>
<br>
&quot;Who are Mongar and Taffy?  You live if you tell me who they are.&quot;  The goblin was dumbstruck.  He tried to say something but his raspy breath only came out as a pitiful. <br>
<br>
&quot;Who. . .  Who . . . Who. . .&quot;   I had kicked to hard.  And he hadn't given me the answer that I was looking for, only another question. <br>
<br>
After the bodies had been disposed, I lit a torch and then went into Runnyeye.<br>
<br>
Blackness upon blackness as I continued to travel through the void.  My mind skipped forward.  I had entered Runnyeye, and I was not assaulted by death, as I had expected, but by swarms of goblins.  They were like fleas that tried to gnaw on my legs, but with controlled rage I dispatched of the vermin, and continued through.  My search was for Mongar--who I had thought was the head goblin--but he was elusive.  I found only junk that included, soot-blackened armor, baubles made of semi-precious stones, and masks that I assumed, the goblins had used, to make them appear less grotesque.  Eventually, I found my way to the Gorge.<br>
<br>
<br>
Chapter 3<br>
<br>
As I traveled through the void, my mind had focused on the first days of my new existence.  These were the days that were important to me, and although, I had only three names, I continued on to Southern Karna in hope that my origin would unfold.  I cannot say why I searched, as I cannot say why I continued to breathe, or why someone had rescued me; but I felt that underneath the scars there was a part of me that had been injured far greater than the physical pain that was inflicted to my body.  I was left with a sense of constant uneasiness, a dry kindling of my soul that flared into rage when any beast, animal, or person provoked me.  It had taken me two weeks to cross through the Gorge of King Xorb and into the plains of Sourthern Karana, and during this time, I had learned more about my abilities.  I learned that my fighting techniques were superior to any creature that assaulted me.  I had killed beasts that were part-bull and part-human.  I had disposed of giant lumbering men that had roamed the hills.  I had killed eagles the size of ogres that swooped down at me with their sharp claws.  <br>
<br>
After I arrived in Sourthern Karana, it had taken me a month to find Brother Qwinn, and upon our introductions, I learned that he needed my help.  He, however, could not help me.  I asked him about Mongar and Taffy, but he didn't know of them.  The tast the Brother Qwinn wanted me to complete involvned retrieveing two items that were stolen from him.  The items were the Code of Zan Fi, from the caves of Lavastorm, and the Idol of Zan Fi from the Dungeon of Guk.  The corrupted monks, Targin and Raster, had stolen these items.  I agreed to the quest because Brother Qwinn had given me direction.<br>
<br>
The quest that Brother Qwinn had given to me was difficult, and the corrupted monk did not fall easily.  Targin was a monster anomg monsters.  He had befriended a clan of kobolds.  I lured him out of hiding and killed him.  The other monk, Raster, was not as elusive.  When I found him in the Dungeon of Guk, he was already fighting another monk.  I helped him and killed Raster myself.  I had then laid claim to the Idol of Zan Fi.<br>
<br>
It took me two years to complete Brother Qwinn's task; and upon my return, he gave me a maroon robe.  I was pround to wear the robe, because not only was it an upgrade from the raw sild robe that I had, but it signified my perseverance and diligence.  The next tast that brother Qwinn gave to me would take me across the world to a continent that I knew nothing about.  I was to travel to Kunark to retrieve to magical pipes.  The pipes were in Karnor Castle and Chardok.  I agreed to the quest.<br>
<br>
I tried to remember more of my history.  My mind skipped forward again, but the memory of my life, wich equated to only the past two-and-a-half years, ended, and the present began.  I was stuck between realities.  I was lost in a void where the only subject was myself, and the only objects were the memories that I had.  I needed to reach my destination.<br>
<br>
I cannot say how long I was in the void.  It might have been days or minutes when I saw, in the distance, a faint yellow dot that gradually grew into a shimmering rectangle of light.  I was approaching it fast, and if I did not pass through, I would crash.  Hopefully, I would zone out on the other side of the world.  The light came closer; it wrapped around me head, and the darkness on either side was replaced by a milky panorama.  My eyes contracted, the world came into focus, and I was in a different land.  I have been x-located across the world.  I had made it to Kunark.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
