<br>
I was in an enchnated valley that flowed with life.  On the ground I saw flowers.  Their stems rose shoulder high and then budded outward into plumes of color that splashed upon my senses and left me with a feeling of awe.  They had colors that I had never seen before.  In the distance, trees gently swayed in the frosty autumn wind.  However, the trees' foliage was still green and fresh.  It was as if nature had become vain and ignored the other three seasons but embraced spring, a time when life began.  I was overwhelmed.  In the distance I could here the running of water.  I followed my senses and arrived at a small river that flowed west.<br>
<br>
I reached into my backpack and took out a curde map of Kunark.  I found my location and knew that to get to Karnor Castle, I would have to travel east.  I began to run in this direction, along the river and up a gentle canyon slope.  I continued to follow the river toward the canyon wall, but eventually the land became rugged and the angle of the route increased to a point where I could go no farther.  I was standing in front of a looming facade, a sheer wall whose only scars were tiny caves that emptied life into the valley.  The river that I had followed led into one of these caves, and upon examination, I noticed that the surface of the water had frozen.  I lit a torch and walked cautiously over the brittle lattice.  The path through the cave was difficult and long.  On occasion, I would slip, and my foot would fall into the biting water below; but still I continued forward, with the hope that I would eventually emerge in the frozen tundra that would lead me to Karnor Castle.  It took the entire night to travel through the cave, and I felt a sense of relief when I finally emerged.  <br>
<br>
The early morning sky was a friendly greeting, and the sun's rays thawed out my chilled body.  I was in a different land.  I had left the enchanted valley, and what lay before my eyes was startling.  In front of me, frozen mountains pierced through the hardened armor of the ground below.  Their peaks angled sharply as they rose.  Between the mountains, there were valleys cut at odd angles.  They were deep crevices that cast strange shadows upon the snowy hills.  Pictures could almost be seen in them.  I was entranced as I stood at the edge of the cave looking outward, over the many miles I would traverse.   <br>
<br>
I traveled through, between, and over mountains.  The journey was difficult.  Occasionally, I would slip and my body would free fall, but I would recover; I was safe.  I continued for days, rarely eating and sleeping.  On some nights I could here the distant barking of dogs, and on others, whispers appeared to float carelessly on the wind.  <br>
<br>
After days of travel, the temperature warmed and the frozed mountains melted away to small hills of slushy snow.  Life was no longer shy and emerged unabashed, as I crossed fields of small shrubbery and twisted trees.  Eventually, I entered a barren area, and in the distance, I saw Karnor Castle. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xtcxtc2000>xtcxtc2000</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/16/03 8:56:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Story Continued</span><hr size=1> Chapter 5<br>
<br>
As I approached Karnor Castle, my light jog turned into a timid walk.  The castle was magnificent but threatening.  It shot upwards to the sky and seemed to extend beyond the boundaries of structural design.  Surrounding the caslte, there was a wall that blocked the entrance to the main structure.  <br>
<br>
It took me an hour to reach Karnor Castle.  I had planned to enter the castle with stealth, but as I circled it, the only entrance that could be seen was the main gate along the west wall.  I slowly crept up toward the gate, slinking between the lonely plinths and fallen columns that were on the outskirts.  I entered some ruined houses.  I believed that these had once been servant quarters, but they had been abandoned.  From these dwelling I could see the entrance, but I could also see two creatures standing guard.  They blocked my way.<br>
<br>
My eyes widened at the sight of these beasts.  They were like sketches from a pervese mind, sketches that had magically popped out of a drawing and now stood animate, alive, and in all dimensions.  The creatures were a mix of human and dog.  They had hairy bodies, long ears, dewlaps, and snouts, yet they stood on two legs.  On occoasion, the half-dogs would communicate with one another, but, unlike a dog's bark, their whines and snorts were distinct and purposeful.  In addition, the half-dogs wore clothes and carried weapons.<br>
<br>
Each half-dog wore a red leather tunic.  In the center of the tunic was a large bronze insignia that bore the image of a lizard-like creature that floated above a jeweled throne.  They had no other clothes but wielded rusty swords that scraped across the ground.<br>
<br>
Judging the strength of something I had never fought was impossible.  The half-dogs might have outmatched me, but I realized that it was better to learn their strength outside the castle rather than trying to sneak in.  If things went bad, I would have time to flee.  Looking around the ruins, I saw some small rocks.  I picked one up, jumped out from where I was hidden, and threw it with all my strength.  I heard a hollow thud and then a yelp.<br>
<br>
It was as if the half-dog had been stung by a bixie.  He roared and left his post.  I ducked down and waited.  His padded footsteps gave away his location.  He was approaching along the west wall.  I shifted positions and hid in a doorway that would intercept his path.  I was facing the wall he would be approaching, but I was out-of-sight.  I crouched to the ground as his shadow crossed the doorway, and then his  maw, and then his body.  The beast was still oblivious to my exact location; I realized that he was searching for me with his sense of smell.  I had my chance; I struck.<br>
<br>
Knuckles collided into ribs and ribs collided into internal organs as his chest gave way to my focused fist.  Before he could howl in pain; I struck again, this time with my foot that became a blunted weapon that raised deftly, but then exploded downward toward his knee.  His leg arched into a &quot;V&quot; shape and he crumpled to the ground.  A quick kick to the throat, and he was dead.  His friend had taken notice and was whimpering as he approached.  He had been instilled with doubt, but not enough to make him tuck tail and flee.  He ambled forward between the ruined buildings, preparing himself; but before he was in striking distance he stopped sharply and started to flail at his back.  The half-dog made a muffled howl and then fell face down onto the ground.  I saw a small puncture wound in his loin.  His body twitched and then went rigid.<br>
<br>
I heard a voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;If you were wondering, it was poison, but step into the shadows--[i]now[/i]--step over here.&quot;  The voice said.  Whomever this was had helped me, but I was reluctant as I moved toward the voice.  I stepped into a building where the voice had originated, and I saw a wood-elf.  He was wiping the blood off his dagger.<br>
<br>
The wood-elf had dark skin and pointed ears.  His face was delicate, almost childlike, but due to his race's longevity, I was unable to make a guess as to his age.  The wood-elf continued to wipe the blood from the blade.  When he was done, he sheathed the weapon, looked up at me, and grinned a smile that impressed the words mischief and mayhem into my mind.  &quot;They are called drovlongs.  Nice little critters aren't they?&quot;  He said.<br>
<br>
&quot;You kill a lot of them?&quot;  I asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yup, I like to have fun.&quot;  I nodded, and extended my hand.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Turan,&quot;  I said, &quot;And thanks!&quot; as we clasped.<br>
<br>
&quot;Devalon Deback, and as you probably know, there's no use in pretending that you don't know my trade.&quot;  I nodded.  His backstab was the tell-tale sign of his class.  He was a rogue.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Well. . . I am a monk.&quot;  I said.<br>
<br>
&quot;I can see that.  I have seen you type enter Karnor.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Why?  What were they here for?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The same thing that you are, I assume.  You have come for the pipe.  You do know how to get to it, right?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, but I can manage.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That is what all the monks say, and some have gotten close, but they always die.  It's such a shame that they try to get the pipe alone and never ask for help.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Would you help me?&quot;  I asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wouldn't help you. . . unless there is something in it for me, and there is.  I left Karnor to find help.  I was hired by some high-elves to retrieve some trinkets from inside.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Where are you friends now?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They are trapped inside, in a small room.  They are stupid, but rich.  I was going to leave, but they doubled, then tripled my commission, and I agreed to find help.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok.  For now I will go with you, but if you try anything, you will find that I'm not the easiest person to kill, rob, or betray.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Normally, I would have relied on myself and ignored Devalon.  However, I was intrigued, and for a strange reason, I felt a connection to him.  I almost knew what it was like to be a rogue.  In addition, what he said was correct.  I did not know the layout of the castle, nor did I know the location of the pipe.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xtcxtc2000>xtcxtc2000</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/20/03 8:59:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Continued</span><hr size=1> Chapter 6<br>
<br>
We entered Karnor through the main gate.  The thick outer wall was constructed our of a porous stone.  This stone, as I would later find out, constructed the entirty of Karnor Castle.  It had a mottled appearance and was stained white and brown.  On the walls of the structure, I saw carved images illuminated by torches.  The images were of armed birds that stood upright.  On the ground, we saw bones of various races and piles of excrement that reeked with stench.  I felt uneasy and slightly nervous.  It was almost as if Karnor had a presence, an aura that breathed our fear and digested those brave enough to enter.<br>
<br>
We rounded a bend, and standing guard were two more drovlongs.  The drovlongs were standing post and were oblivious to our presence.  Behind the dogs was a drawbridge that led to a guard tower.  I could see more drovlongs standing upon a ledge that jutted outward.  Above this ledge the buildling contained no more outcroppings but had narrow slitted windows that were commonly used for archers.  This was not a regal castle, but a fortress constructed for defense.  The two drovlongs that were in front of us were larger that the ones outside.  Ther garb was similiar.  <br>
<br>
&quot;They don't move,&quot;  Devalon said.<br>
<br>
&quot;The two ouside didn't move either, until I hit one with a rock.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They are static; whoever, created them didn't bother to give them much intelligence.  Their only purpose is to guard the drawbridge.  If they atack us where we stand, someone could sneak in from behind.&quot;  I nodded.<br>
<br>
&quot;Is there another way around?&quot;  I said.  Devalon pointed to the moat.  <br>
<br>
&quot;We could swim through the moat, but that route is not the best.  It takes us to the sewers.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Which way then?&quot;  Devalon pointed straight.<br>
<br>
&quot;You attack these two, but be careful.  Another one roams behind.  I will sneak behind these and. . .&quot;  He poked his thumb into his palm, his palm fell down, and I understood his plan.<br>
<br>
&quot;Let's do it!&quot;  I said, but Devalon had disappeared.  I was a solo monk, with a dark shadow that I was beginning to like.  More rusty weapons were being wielded by the drovlongs, this time a spear and a morning star.  I was confident as I approached.  They saw me and slowly advanced.  I charged the drovlong with the spear.<br>
<br>
I cut the distance, rolled low, and struck the drovlong with an uppercut between its legs.  He howled.  My attention shifted to the dog holding the mace, which was now coming down in a wide overhead arc aimed at my head.  As I jumped to the side, the mace thudded loudly into the ground sending chips of stone flying.  He swung again and clipped me in the arm.  I was abashed; I had underestimated his adroit reflexes.  I steadied myself and motioned him forward.  His maw lunged down at me.  I side-stepped, he missed, and his body was low.  I jumped onto his back, my legs locked around his chest, and my arms wrapped around his face.  My fingers found the dog's eyes and I pulled back with all my weight.  I felt his eyes collapse inward, creating two new grotesque handhold for my fingers that were now covered in a wet slime.  He thrashed about and I alghted.  My next attack was a flurry of punches.  he crashed to the floor, dead, or soon to be.  <br>
<br>
The other drovlong had regained his comosure.  His voice was an octave higher as he hobbled forward, driven by anger.  Then I saw it.  Devalon's dagger cut through the shadow and he pierced through the drovlong's red tunic and into red below.  He then rotated his body so that he was face-to-face with the dog, his short-sword flew up, then down, in a quick arc.  More cuts from the blade and the dog was dead.  &quot;Easy, ain't it?&quot;  Devalon said, as he looted the corpse.  I nodded.  &quot;Now we go slow.&quot;  He pushed the corpses into the moat.<br>
<br>
We walked across the drawbridge, through the guard tower, and over another small drawbridge that led into the castle.  &quot;This way,&quot; Devalon said as he pointed in a direction that led left and into a courtyard.  When we entered, his pace slowed and he faced me.  &quot;Last night--here--a group of three got slaughtered.  They were trying to break through, but they weren't strong enough.&quot;  I saw what Devalon meant.  In the southwest corner of the courtyard, I saw three corpses: two male humans and a wood-elf female.  <br>
<br>
Devalon pointed at the bodies.  &quot;Warriors, both of them, and the girl, well, she was a druid.&quot;  I approached the corpses because I wanted insight as to what we would be fighting later.  The bodies were a mess; one of the male's armor had been pierced through in spots and a thin layer of blood stained the circumference of each hole.  The other male's body had lost its head.  His hands still grasped tightly at his neck.  The wood-elf female, the worst of the three, appeared to have no protection from what assaulted her.  Her wounds were deep cuts that were split like tiny lips, wetted white, and then placed strategically over the majority of her body.  Devalon looked down at them and said, &quot;They couldn't fight worth a damn, and they picked a terrible place to camp.  We heard their screams last night, but there was nothing that we could do.&quot;  Looking away, I felt nervous, and a sense of urgency arose.<br>
<br>
&quot;Are we close to your friends?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, follow me.&quot;  In the courtyard that we were in, there were three routes that we could take.  We chose the one that led to the second floor of the main castle.  We acended a circular staircase and emerged in a long corridor that we followed west.  The corridor ended, and we found ourselves outside, on a walkway, that extended along the perimeter of the castle.  The perimieter was narrow and ran along the second floor of the castle.  From here we went north, past a parapet, and proceeded, past a series of rooms that were part of the main structure.  &quot;We're here,&quot; Devalon said, as he pointed to, and then opended, a small wooden door.<br>
<br>
