<br>
When I saw Devalon's friends, I realized why he had recruited me.  The three high-elves sitting quietly in the corner looked feeble and weak, not tall and radiant like I had expected.  The two female high-elves were meditating and barely glanced up when we entered.  In addition, their features of the seed were alike, as both had dull blue eyes, an extended jawline, large noses, and slightly crooked teeth.  They looked identical.  &quot;Twins&quot;   Devalon told me as I glanced at them.<br>
<br>
The high-elf male was as thin as an old parchment, and as fragile also.  He looked as if his diet consisted of black bread and globular water.  &quot;Is this the help that you found?&quot;  he said.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is Turan, a monk who is going to help us,&quot;  Devalons said.  I extended my hand to the high-elf.  He ignored the gesture.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I am Pallorid, the white elf, a noble paladin that fights for justice.  I carry Soulfire a mighty blade that enervates my body with strength and power.  I am the gratuitous protector of the twins.  I am the beginning of the end for all that is evil and loathe.  I am the vanquisher that vanquishes those that should be vanquished.  I am--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Nice to meet you,&quot; I groaned.  The twins glanced up from their spell books.  Both of them were ghostly white making it hard to tell where their white robes ended and where they began.<br>
<br>
&quot;Genna Coteria,&quot; one said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Genna is the Enchanter,&quot;  Devalon said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Jeanna Coteria,&quot; said the other.<br>
<br>
&quot;Jeanna is the wizard. . . I call them the silent duo.&quot;  Devalon looked down at the twins.  &quot;Genna, Jeanna, tell Turan what you are looking for.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We are here for bracelets.  Magical bracelets that are supple, beautiful, and when worn will grant us more intelligence,&quot; one of the twins said.<br>
<br>
In addition to the high-elves, there was also a dwarf in the room.  He wore cobalt blue armor which was dented in places.  He was sleeping and his snores were alarmingly loud.  &quot;Who is that?&quot;  Devalon said.<br>
<br>
&quot;We found someone also,&quot; Pallorid said.<br>
<br>
&quot;I can see that.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;His name is Apoprage.  He is a warrior who stumbled into the room earlier.  He is willing to help if Jeanna evacuates him when we are done.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Great,&quot; Devalon said.  He appeared carefree and unburdened by his surroundings.  This bothered me.  It was as if nothing mattered to him, a fact that was not surprising.  I guessed by his trade, he was capable of sneaking out of Karnor on a whim.<br>
<br>
After the introductions had been made, Devalon called me over.  &quot;Let's talk strategy.  When night falls, you are going to be the bait.  I need you to lure mobs back to the room.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Sure,&quot; I asseneted; I didn't mind this request because if I was the bait, I could control the number and type we would be facing.  Devalon pointed beyond the door and motioned in the direction we had come from.  &quot;Continue on that way.  The path breaks right then loops around to a jail.  the jail has some dogs and a few skeletons.  Leave them be.  Past the jail, there is a staircase that leads down to a room with four dogs.  In this room there are four Drovlong Warlords.  They are large dogs that command the others; they are the targets, and the biggest one has your pipe.&quot;  I nodded.<br>
<br>
&quot;What direction should I start from?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;First bring in the ones that are roaming: skeleton, dog, or ghost, it doesn't matter.  We will fight in this room, since it is secluded and large.  After these mobs are cleared, go to the Warlords and try to lure the biggest Warlord out.  He is the one that has the pipe.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How will I know that he will have it?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You don't, but if he doesn't, we will kill the other Warlords, and then, I will go down there and search the room for.  After you get the pipe, you promised to stay and help the others.  I need your help also; I need the commission.  I don't know where the bracelets are, but the elves keep insisting that the Warlords have them.  If we don't find any bracelets, i have a few of my own that I can slip on the corpses.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;If you have the bracelets already, why didn't you sell them to the high-elves?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;They don't know what they look like, so they wouldn't trust me.  They shouldn't trust me either, because the ones that I have are fake.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What if you have an extra pipe also?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't--the pipe is here for sure--I know it is.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How do you know?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, you remember when I told you that lots of monks have entered and few have left.  They always die close to here.&quot;  That sounded reassuring.  Devalon patted me on the back and sighed.  &quot;We are both rogues, Turan, searching for things; I admit the fact, but you are in denial.  If you trust me, things will work out.&quot;  I didn't reply, nor did I trust him.  He had an answer to any question that I asked, and they all seemed to make complete sense.  However, what really bothered me was Devalon's over-friendly attitude toward me.<br>
