During the remainder of the afternoon we rested and prepared.  The elves secluded themselves in the corner and chatted in their native tongue.  Occasionally I would llisten, and although I could not speak High-Elf, I enjoyed hearing their melodic language.  It was one of their few redeeming qualities.  During the day, from time-to-time, Devalon would leave to scout the area.  He would return with a smile and say &quot;one less that we have to worry about.&quot;  I couldn't tell if he was joking.  For me, the remainder of the afternoon was spent in thought.  <br>
<br>
As a monk, I always tried to find a purpose in my surroundings, but in Karnor, it was hard.  I knew that the rewards from the quest were great, but the reasons behind my efforts did not lie in the material, but the immaterial treasure that I hoped to receive.  I hoped to gain knowledge about my past.  However, during the three years that I had been doing the quest, nothing had been revealed other than the dreams that I had.  And there were not reliable, for who is to know, whether the images that I saw were: events of my past, fiction of the present, or omens of the future.  <br>
<br>
The dreams came to me each night.  I would often dream of my only friend; I missed Lum's quirky attitude and kindness.  On these nights, I was blessed, because on others, I was assaulted by nightmares.  I often saw my own death in many different ways.  The dreams never made sense, but still, I clung to them.  I cherished the idea that I had gained a part of my memory back, when in actuality, I hadn't.  These are the thoughts that occupied my mind, but as the afternoon waned, I thought about the task at hand, the quest, and my unfortunate predicament of being stuck in a castle with a rogue, and four naive heros.  I was not attuned to working with others.  And even though I like Devalon and his nonchalant attitude, I would be a fool to trust a rogue.  But I had no choice; I needed the pipe.<br>
