<br>
As the hours passed, the sun bowed out, and the moon made its nightly cameo, lauded with praise from the cacophony of barks and howls heard in the distance.  It was time to start fighting.  I was ready, and I exited the room.  Torch light illuminated the walkways that I would be navigating, and the moon, now center stage, made the castle glow with an eerie light.  It was sufficient, but not ideal.  <br>
<br>
I walked north toward the jail and then cut right, down a small corridor that led into the main structure of the castle.  I continued down this corridor and rounded a bend that broke left.  Upon rounding the bend, I saw what appeared to be a floating shadow, but unlike a shadow, the features of the apparation were distinct.  It felt as if I was looking both through and at him simultaneously.  The form appeared to be Iksar.  It had a long scaled tail and a rounded oval-shaped head.  The shadow was close, a dwarf-toss away.  It turned on me.  I slowly crept backwards toward the room.  The ghost started to move in my direction; its forked tongue flicked in-and-out of its mouth.  I dashed back to the room.  I heard his padded footsteps behind me.  <br>
<br>
The door crashed open, and I ran in yelling &quot;Ghost! Ghost!&quot;  Three small Dravlongs entered the room.<br>
<br>
Those aren't ghosts,&quot; Apoprage shouted.  He was right, I had picked them up on the way back.  Apoprage was the closest to the dogs, near the door, and he began to swing his blades in wide looping arcs that lacked precision or control.  We were in trouble; he looked like a child in his first fight.  He was swinging blindly, hoping to make contact.  Devalon and I watched the spectacle, incredulous, and scared to approach, lest we be struck down by friend.<br>
<br>
&quot;Help, you cowards!&quot;  Apoprage yelled.  He was blocking the door and pushing the dogs out.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Get back--<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fool</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.&quot; Devalon said.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Cowards! Cowards!&quot; Apoprage screamed as he struck one dog with the flat of his blade.  The dog fell backwards out of the room.  Apoprage followed it.  Devalon looked at me.<br>
<br>
&quot;Turan, let's go.&quot;  We exited the room; the three high-elves remained.  On the walkways, we could see the ghost; he was close to the door.  His hands were bathed in a blue light and I knew that he was casting a spell.  I saw this and struck him with a round kick that sent him crashing into the wall.  It was as if I had kicked a bubble of air, but my foot was still effective.  He was pinned and I struck out again at the dis-corporeal entity, with a mighty punch, but I felt only stone as the ghost vanished through the wall.  I felt a slight pop in my hand, my mouth lost control, and I howled at the moon.  <br>
<br>
Apoprage laughed, &quot;Ghosts, you fool.&quot;  He and Devalon were still battling the dogs.  They had killed one, and each was busy with another.  The ghost, as I had expected, had warped through the wall, and into the room.  I heard Pallorid's high-pitched battle cry.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm getting the ghost,&quot; I said.  Devalon nodded.  I entered the room.  My hand was still throbbing, sending bolts of pain up-and-down my arm.  My left arm had been disabled.  In the room, Pallorid was fighting the ghost who was trying to cast its spells.  Its hand would flash blue, then red, but Pallorid's wild swings were interrupting the process.  Its back was turned to me. <br>
<br>
I flew through the air with leg extended.  My foot clapped as thunder on the back of the ghost's head sending it forward into Pallorid's sword.  Its body went limp, and its form dissipated into a fine white powder that sprinkled to the ground.  Apoprage and Devalon entered the room.  <br>
<br>
&quot;We won, but it was an ugly fight,&quot; Devalon said.  That is how I felt also.  I looked down at my hand and frowned; two of my knuckles had disappeared.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Why so many!&quot; Pallorid yelled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shut up, or maybe you want to go out next time,&quot; Devalon admonished.  Pallorid capitulated.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Come over here, Turan; let me get you hand fixed up.  I can heal you.  Next time--be careful.&quot;<br>
<br>
I nodded and agreed.  After Pallorid had healed my minor wound, we rested briefly.  I sat alone in a corner with Devalon.<br>
<br>
&quot;What do you think of our four friends?&quot;  Devalon asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Novices.  They are going to get us killed.  Apoprage is frightfully aggressive, Pallorid is--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah.  Yeah.  I know,  we're not going to be here long.  I have a plan.  You know the bracelets that I told you about earlier--the fake ones?  I'm going to slip them onto the Drovlong Warlord after you get your pipe.  If I do this, they'll be happy and ready to leave.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Good idea, let's get out of here. . . after we get the pipe.&quot;  I didn't feel guilty about what Devalon had planned to do.  The others had no business in Karnor, and Devalon's trick would probably save their lives.  &quot;It's obvious that they can't fight; why did you accompany them to being with?&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm a guide&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;So you escort would be heros on quests?  for a fee right?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I make money, but I deserve it.  You wouldn't believe the fools that I see.  All around.  Sometimes--&quot; he said as he slapped his forward with the palm of his hand--&quot;I think that I am going to go crazy!  And these elves, and their dwarf friend are fools.  Utter fools with the milk included.&quot;  He pointed to the high-elves.  <br>
<br>
&quot;That's crazy Devalon.  Isn't it dangerous?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah it is, many have died, but they would have died anyway.  The high-elves, if I had not helped, might have got lost on the way to Karnor Castle.  If they were lucky and had made it here, they would have never made it to this room.  You see, Turan, I'm just the map that guides them, but, unlike a map, I can fight.  I'm saving lives and getting paid in the process.&quot; I laughed.<br>
<br>
&quot;A noble rogue?&quot;  Devalon paused, looked at me, and for a second I thought that I could see a hint of sadness in his eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;My conscious is--bleh, I don't have to explain myself to you Turan.  You ask too many questions.  But, I don't care for these high-elves, and that is why I'm going to slip the fake bracelets onto the Warlord.  I would have earlier--I didn't know how pathetic they were--but I will not leave till you get you pipe.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But Devalon, why does it matter if I succeed or fail?<br>
<br>
&quot;It doesn't really, but. . . I'm starting to like you.  A little.  And if you do get it, you'll probably go after the second one and accompany me to Chardok.  There is something that I want, and I could use your help.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What do you want in Chardok?&quot;  I asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;A certain sarnak's head,&quot; he said as he drew his finger across his throat.<br>
<br>
&quot;Whose?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You ask too many questions, Turan.  And I bet I can guess your next one also.  You are going to ask, 'but Devalon how do you know about my--secret monk quest?'&quot; he said as he imitated my low voice.  &quot;I'll explain it to you later.  But now, go do your job!&quot;<br>
