<br>
I was more cautious of the beasts that would be tailing me.  It was hard, and on occasion, I had to be creative, but I brought them back solo.  Usually Devalon got the killing blow, as his abilities were greater than those of the elves and dwarf.  When Devalon attacked, each of his blows landed with precision.  The slightest cut from his blade or pierce from his dagger seemed to have deadly effects.  <br>
<br>
Apoprage and Pallorid--as I had learned earlier--were not so adept in blade nor intellct; however, they did serve a purpose.  Pallorid healed my minor wounds, and Apoprage's fierce yells and overbearing appearance attracted the monsters as they entered the room.  This would allow Devalon to sneak around and kill the mobs from behind.  The high-elf twins were still book-bound and were barely aware of what was happeneing.  The process repeated as I slowly made my way toward the jail.  <br>
<br>
After I had cleared a path to the jail, I informed the group that the next mob was going to be from the Warlord room.  I left the room and made my way down the corridor.  The castle now seemed deserted because the numberous spawns that were roaming earlier had temporarily been disposed of.  I passed the jail, ignored the skeletal fingers and furry paws which groped between the bars, and the proceeded down a circular set of stairs toward the Warlord Room.  At the bottom of the stairs was a door.  I opened it and entered.  <br>
<br>
It was mealtime for the Drovlong Warlords, and on the menu was elf and dwarf.  That is how I saw them when I entered the room, sitting at a table eating adventurors and telling them in the process.  They were the largest dogs I had seen.  They were two-trolls-tall and viscous looking.  Each Drovlong Warlord was armed with a sword sheathed at their waists .   They looked up from the meal, licked their lips, and probably saw me as dessert.  I turned and darted up the stairs.<br>
<br>
When I passed the jail, I stopped and waited with poise; my shoulders bobbed up-and-down.  The largest dog appeared first, followed by the other three.  He motioned the others back.  They barked in complaince and retreated toward the staircase.  &quot;A dog with honor,&quot; I thought as I chuckled to myself.  The largest dog attacked.  His sword was not drwan; for him, paws and maw were enough.  He raked at me; I dodged.  My mind focused, and I avoided his attacks.  His third blow was a haymaker, aimed at my head; I rolled, but the blow struck me.  I toppled to the floor.  <br>
<br>
The attacks ceased, and I heard him bark out a command.  The other dogs were leaving, walking down the staircase that led back to the Warlord Room.  They had been split, and I was alone with the biggest Drovlong Warlord.  &quot;The plain is working.  It's working,&quot; I thought.  <br>
<br>
I heard the rusty scrape of his sword leaving its sheath.  His furry paw reached down and grabbed my wrist.  He lifted me up, and I knew his intention.  Dangling from hooks on his armor were slabs of dired meat that included a collection of paws, feet, and other body parts.  They were his trophies, and my hand was going to added to the collection.  &quot;Got to be fast.  Got to be fast.  I need my hand,&quot;  I thought. <br>
<br>
The raised sword flew at my wrist, but as this occured, my dangling feet became fixed on the ground and my once limp arm shot up and met his elbow.  My blow steered the blade off-course and into the wall.  Immediately, I struck upward, into his maw.  He released me, and I crept backward.  &quot;Follow me, follow me, &quot; I thought.  The drovlong howled, but slowly advanced.  The dog was wounded; his nose was spurting blood in tune to each ragged breath, but still he advanced.  His gaze was fixed and in hazy eyes, I was the target.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Come to me.  Come on, don't get your friends,&quot; I thought.  I limped backward and pretended that my death was close.  I shook my hands.  &quot;No more--please--no more.  I will leave,&quot;  I said hopeing that he understood my ragged Common.  I rounded the corner that led back to the room and continued creeping backward.  We were now face-to-face.  The Drovlong Warlord charged, but I had reached the door.  I opened it and dashed inside.  <br>
<br>
With a growl he followed me through, but with a whine he was cut down, not at the neck, but at his ankles that tripped over the low swords held by Pallorid and Apoprage who were crouched adjacent to either side of the door.  His stature decreased and his composure followed as he toppled to the floor.  Devalon ended the dog with a slash to the throat.  <br>
<br>
My heart pounded from both adrenaline and anticipation, as Devalon searched the corpse.  He looked at me and smiled. &quot;This is yours,&quot; he said.  He threw a hollow metal pipe toward me.  <br>
<br>
It was not what I had expected.  The pipe looked plain.  It was not made of valuable metal, nor was it layered with precious stones.  However, in my hands, I felt a sense of happiness surge through my body.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Is this it?&quot; I asked.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.  Not, what you expected. . . I know, but it's the one,&quot; Devalon said.  Jeanna and Genna had finally removed their noses from their spell books.  They had yet to do anything to help.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Do they have the bracelets?&quot; one of the twins asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Suppple, beautiful, and made of ivory, &quot; Devalon said as he held up two plain bracelets.  The twins cheered at the fake baubles.  Inside, I was laughing.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Let's get out of here.&quot; I said.  <br>
<br>
&quot;But are there more bracelets?  Surely, there are more to be found.  You gave us only two, and we need one for each wrist,&quot; the twins said in unison.  I shook my head.  Apoprage stomped his foot on the ground and grumbled.  <br>
<br>
&quot;You heard the monk--no more--<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>bracelets</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.&quot;  The twins ignored Apoprage.  And with rueful countenance asked again.<br>
<br>
&quot;Can you check around Mr. Monk. one more time, just once more?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;There are no more Drovlong Warlords; there was only the one that we killed.  He was the only one that I saw,&quot; I said.  Devalon nodded his head.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Turan says that there are no more.  Please, don't be such a greedy--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Bitch,&quot; I thought to myself.  My eyes widened as I watched the door crash open.  The remaining Drovlong Warlords entered.  It was my first thought, and it was quite appopriate.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Back wall!&quot; Devalon yelled.  <br>
<br>
&quot;You lie.  What are those?  What are those?&quot; one of the twins yelled as she pointed to the three large Warlords.  <br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Back wall</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->! Devalon yelled again.  <br>
<br>
We regrouped as the snarling dogs approached.  The Drovlong Warlords were not alone, and four of the smaller ones entered after them.  &quot;Now we will see what you're made of,&quot; Devalon said to me.  He had a grin on his face.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Crazy, crazy rogue,&quot; I thought.  <br>
<br>
The twins were behind us and apparently forgotten thier earlier query.  They were beginning to chant.  <br>
<br>
The drovlongs attacked in unison, boring into our huddled group with sword and claw.  I parried and blocked and struck out, but when the dogs came in numbers, it was hard to find a weakness.  Jeanna--who was the wizard--ended her spell first.  Her fingers sparked blue, and energy as controlled lightning shot outward from her fingertips and collided with the dogs.  The Drovlong Warlords were knocked back from the force of the spell.  They crashed into the wall near the door.  One of the smaller dogs, which had been hit, flew through the open door, over the small wall, and into the moat below.<br>
<br>
&quot;Get us out!&quot; Devalon yelled.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Get close and hold them off for a minute!&quot;  Jeanna said.  She began to cast her next spell.  <br>
<br>
Genna--the enchanter--who had also been casting, finsihed her spell.  She pointed her hands toward me.  A sense of power shot through my nose and mouth; I felt euphoric.  The spell that she had cast, sped up my reflexes and tweaked my will.  My mouth became dry, my jaw started to clench, and i felt invincible.  It was ecstasy undermined by the annoying reality that possible death was in front of me.  My mind mind began to rave.  I needed to kill the dogs because I needed to be alone.  I needed to enjoy whatereve she did.  <br>
<br>
I charged a Warlord that was approaching, and, in my tempered haste, brought him down with a flurry of punches.  Genna cast her spell again, and this time Devalon got a hit.  He sprang into action, his sword and dagger became a dervish blur that slashed at the dogs.  I killed another with a punch to the temple.  We were winning, but more were entering the room.  They seperated our group.  Jeanna completed here second spell.  More lightning, and fragments of dogs flying across, out, and around the room like plush toys in the wake of a child's tantrum.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Get us out, you stupid prig,&quot;  Devalon hollered.  Jeanna began to cast again.  <br>
<br>
&quot;No more lightning.  No more lighting.  Just Evacuate us,&quot; I thought.  I looked about.  At least six dogs were in the room.  Twelve arms were attacking us, and one finally got lucky.  I heard a yell.  The Drovlong that Apoprage had been fighting had found flesh, split flesh, and severed flesh.  He was dead.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Get us out.  Please,&quot;  I thought again.  The room was going crazy.  And Pallorid--the high-elf paladin--began to panic.  He ran for the door.  He swung his sword like a mad-elf, as he struck anything in his path, but escaping to the door was probably equivelent to running blindfolded and naked through Kithicor at night.  I'm not sure how he died, but something got him along the way.  <br>
<br>
Finally, Genna finished her spell, and a new hope arose.  With hands aimed high, she directed a prismatic pulse of energy that flowed toward the drovlongs.  They stopped attacking and tottered about in a trance.  Some of the dogs smiled and grasped at the air with their furry paws.  Others cringed and whimpered.  They were like living statues stuck in time, stuck in a moment where emotions, good or bad, culminate and focus to a point where the only escape is to shut-down.  &quot;They are mesmerized!&quot;  Genna shouted as she ran across the room.  &quot;Now, get us out!&quot; she screamed to Jeanna, the wizard.  <br>
<br>
Jeanna, finally, completed her spell.  I sighed with relief as milky white cloud engulfed the room.  There was a flash of light; the twins had vanished.  Devalon and I looked at each other with bewildered expressions.  The dogs were still in a trance.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Where did they go?  Where did they go?&quot;  I asked.  <br>
<br>
&quot;They evacuated, but they forgot to take us with them!&quot;  One of the dogs broke free of the enchanter's spell.  He lunged at Devalon.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Devalon!&quot; I yelled. He sidestepped, and I struck the drovlong down.  I glanced about the room.  Another dog came out of its trance and then another.  The world was coming back to life.  &quot;What now?&quot;  I asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Run</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->!&quot; Devalon screamed as he dashed through the door.  I followed him and slammed the door on the room of drovlongs.  And for an instant, I believed the adage that said that out of sight is out of mind.  <br>
<br>
We were now on the walkway, but on either side, more dogs were blocking our escape.  One of the dogs charged at us.  Devalon swung low with his short-sword, the dog reeled and Devalon shoved him over the walkway into the moat.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Can you swim?&quot;  Devalon asked.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;Too many--more are coming--I'm going to hide.  Meet me later outside the castle, but you,&quot;--he pointed to the water--&quot;Swim.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;What about you?&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;Go--I will be fine,&quot; Devalon said as he slashed at another drovlong who lunged at us.  <br>
<br>
I looked over the small wall and jumped.  The water below rushed up at me, and when I hit, I became disoriented.  I began to swim toward the drawbridge that would take me out of Karnor.  The swim was strenuous.  The water was like mud.  It clogged my nose and stung my eyes.  Overhead I could hear the barks of frantic drovlongs; Karnor was in a frenzy.  The journey was short, but when I crawled out of the brackish water, it felt like I had just swum across Lake Rathe.  I was exhausted.  A voice called out to me.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Turan.  Turan.  Come over here!&quot;  I shook my head and wiped the sludge out of my eyes.  &quot;Turan.  Turan--fast--come over here!&quot; the voice repeated.  I looked up.  The twins were sixty feet in front of me.  &quot;It was an accident, we didn't mean to leave.  Fast.  We will get you out.&quot;  Genna was gesticulating wildly with her arms.  I began to walk toward them.  Jeanna--the wizard--was casting again.  I assumed it was another evacuation spell.  I couldn't care less where it took them, as long as it took me also.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm coming,&quot; I said as I began to jog toward them.<br>
<br>
&quot;Train!  Train!  Behind you!&quot; Genna shouted.  I could barely understand her screams.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.  Yes.  I'm coming, hold on.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No! Train!  Train!  Behind you!&quot;  She yelled as she pointed beyond me.  <br>
<br>
I turned.  My pupils widened.  It was as if death was approaching me.  I had felt this feeling before and it had scarred me.  I had been lucky; I had cheated death, but now, it had returned and was charging at me like a battering ram.  It was overkill.  It was an army, a legion, of dogs, skeletons, and ghosts rushing toward us.  <br>
<br>
I made it to the twins, but the spell wasn't fast enough.  We were overtaken. Instinctively, my feet became one with the ground.  My muscles tensed.  They became hard like stone.  The twins were not as lucky.  They had no protection and were beaten into the ground; Karnor Castle had two new white stains.  <br>
<br>
My concentration was about to break, and when this happened I would be the third smear.  Death was my only option.  My muscles relaxed and the rain of blows turned into a storm that pounded down upon me.  Something struck me in the stomach.  Something slashed at my arm.  My body became limp and I fell to the ground.  My heart rate slowed, and my eyes stared blankly at the dogs above, but my play at death wasn't convincing.  It had failed, and now I was being killed.  It was happening again, and this time I doubted that Lum would be around to save me.  I willed myself dead again because I needed to live.  This time, the dogs believed my play at death and slowly backed away.<br>
<br>
It was as if Quellious had smiled and had parted the sea of death with his merciful hand, but I was not safe yet.  Something wrapped around my leg and started to drag me back toward the castle.  In my position, I couldn't see what it was.  <br>
<br>
Then, whatever had grabbed me, lifted me into the air by the leg--Quellious smirked-- and my body was twirled around-and-around in a wide overhead arch.  I screamed out as the world spun before my eyes.  My mind was wracked in pain, and I started to hallucinate.  The drovlongs disappeared, my body shrank in size, and all I could see was a gaint green reanimated hand twirling me around as if my body was a rock and my leg was a sling.  Eventually, it let loose, and I soared through the air and into the moat.   <br>
<br>
I tried to swim down, but waves of pain erupted through my body.  If I surfaced, the dogs would see me.  I do not know what willed me on, but something did.  I refused to be killed by drovlong, ghost, or skeleton.  My air began to wane; my chest felt like it was expanding.  I needed  air; I needed to breath.  My mind cogitated and I thought: &quot;I can not go to the afterlife like this.&quot;  I was a monk with no origin.  I needed to breathe.  And then, something inspired me; I became better than I was before.  I reached into my robe and found the solution.  I removed the pipe and placed to my lips.  It became an extension of my mouth that brought me life when I was close to death.  But this was only the beginning.  <br>
<br>
I waited patiently, and in my underwater grave the simple phrase, &quot;I will survive,&quot; replayed in my head like a scratched record on a gnomish phonograph.  At first I said the phrase with certainty because I was confident that the wavy images above, the drovlongs, who paced back-and-forth, would eventually become bored.  They would give up their search and allow me to creep up and out of Karnor Castle.  But as the minutes passed and the hours emerged, my mantra, which had once felt endearing, became vapid and stale, listless like an inspid platitude that crept out of my mouth and then slowly sank into the murky water below.  <br>
<br>
I was dying.  My lungs felt compressed; each breath taken was strained.  The pipe that had granted me air seemed to have shrunk as each inhalation was a tedious process.  One of my legs--the one which I had been swung by--was limp, and any movement that it made brought waves of pain that cascaded along my back and leg.  I began to shiver; I began to remember the dreams I had.  I wanted to remember the world for what it might have been.  And when this occurred, my mind reversed upon itself and time no longer walked in a straight line.  I started to remember the dreams that I had had in the past three years.  <br>
<br>
I started in the beginning.  I was a child again.  I was playing a game of hide-and-seek, darting through shadowed streets and small alleys.  I crept between the small houses and emerged at a bank.  I approached it, sat down, and opened my palm.  I was cadging coppers in the wealthiest city in Norrath.  An item dropped carelessly to the ground.  I picked the sparkling item up.  It slid into my pocket.  A hand grabbed my wrist.  I felt pain.  I hurt.  <br>
<br>
&quot;It's not that easy,&quot; a voice said.  I had been caught stealing and the price would be my off-hand.  <br>
<br>
&quot;No, I didn't mean to.  I'm hungry.  So hungry.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So you believe you are a rogue?&quot;  the voice said.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I would never stab you in the back,&quot; I replied.  <br>
<br>
&quot;We need to leave.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You. . . You found me.  Why was I tempted to rob you a second time?  I'm so sorry.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;No we need to leave Karnor.  This is Devalon.&quot;  I felt myself being dragged along the ground.  And then the world faded.   <br>
